    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-inputs-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Key input parameters bounded with documented uncertainty",
        "description": "Inlet velocity profile, blood viscosity, and pump geometry tolerances must each have documented uncertainty bounds. Propagated uncertainty on RH must be quantified and reported even where confidence in individual bounds is limited."
      },
      "rationale": "Blood viscosity is the single explicitly-flagged low-confidence input: literature values for shear-thinning parameters span a ±12% range due to donor variability, and no patient-specific measurements were available for this study. This uncertainty is documented honestly. Monte Carlo propagation (500 samples, Latin hypercube) shows viscosity uncertainty contributes 60% of the total RH prediction variance; the resulting 95% CI on RH remains below 1.0 at all operating points. The gap is accepted as residual risk because (a) the upper-bound RH prediction still satisfies the acceptance criterion with margin, and (b) the sensitivity analysis identifies viscosity as the dominant driver, enabling targeted future experimental characterisation. All other inputs (geometry, rotational speed, flow rate) are well-characterised with narrow tolerances. Gradation 2 is achieved."
    },
